'''Sheila Mae Pinkel''' (born 1941) is an American artist best known for her [[Photogram|cameraless photography]] work.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Edwards|first1=Latasha|title=Sheila Pinkel mixes science with photography|url=http://www.thecorsaironline.com/arts-entertainment/2011/02/23/sheila-pinkel-mixes-science-with-photography/|website=The Corsair|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> Her artwork has environmental and political themes, with series about nuclear reactors, U.S. involvement in El Salvador, prisons and the lack of natural grown foods.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Von Blum|first1=Paul|title=Other visions, other voices: women political artists in greater Los Angeles|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America, Inc.|isbn=0-8191-9475-1|page=149}}</ref> Sheila Pinkel was born in [[Newport News, Virginia]]. She attended [[Santa Monica High School]] and [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Bachelor of Arts]] in Art/Sculpture, 1963) before getting her MFA in Art/Photography from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] in 1977. From 1986 - 2012 she was a Professor of Art at [[Pomona College]] in California.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pinkel, Sheila|url=http://www.mocp.org/detail.php?type=related&kv=7569&t=people|website=Museum of Contemporary Photography|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>
